How can we understand these two striking features? Most models or theories focus on either heat as a primary aversive variable that triggers aggression (general aggression model [GAM]; 
 Anderson & Bushman, 2002), or the notion that people are more likely to meet face-to-face during warmer weather where aggression and violence are likely to unfold (routine activity theory; 
 Cohen & Felson, 1979). However, neither of these models can explain the large variation in aggression and violence levels worldwide, such as the enormous homicide differences depicted in 
 Figure 1 (for a discussion, see 
 van Lange et al., 2017b).
